WILL MA: So today
I promised I would

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:25.390
play through the second
half of the tournament

00:00:25.390 --> 00:00:27.670
that I started last
time, so two times ago,

00:00:27.670 --> 00:00:31.320
but before Jennifer
Shahade's guest lecture.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:33.820
But before I start,
so remember last time

00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:35.440
we got to the final table.

00:00:35.440 --> 00:00:37.750
This is essentially the
start of the final table.

00:00:37.750 --> 00:00:40.870
And but before I
get into the hands,

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:43.870
I want to do a bit of
theory first that I've been

00:00:43.870 --> 00:00:45.910
forgoing so far in this class.

00:00:45.910 --> 00:00:49.510
And it's essentially what's
called the independent chip

00:00:49.510 --> 00:00:51.460
mode, or ICM theory.

00:00:51.460 --> 00:00:56.010
And essentially what it's
used for is in tournaments,

00:00:56.010 --> 00:01:00.460
essentially the value of
chips is essentially nonlinear

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:03.700
because you're not really trying
to just get all the chips.

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:05.470
You are trying to last
as long as possible

00:01:05.470 --> 00:01:07.130
and move up the payouts.

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:10.360
So I want to now formally
quantify what this means

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:14.866
and how you calculate the
EV of your game rules.

00:01:14.866 --> 00:01:17.170
So far I think
I've just told you

00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:19.840
everything that's done so far
in this class has been chip EV.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:23.050
And I've told you just
play to maximize chip EV.

00:01:23.050 --> 00:01:24.929
Maximize your expected
number of chips.

00:01:24.929 --> 00:01:26.720
And that's a pretty
reasonable way to play.

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:29.350
In cash games, it's
what you want to do.

00:01:29.350 --> 00:01:32.450
And in tournaments it's
not a bad approximation.

00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:35.150
So I don't want everyone
after this ICM lecture

00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:37.192
to think, you know, I've
got to completely change

00:01:37.192 --> 00:01:39.441
my playing in tournaments
because that's not the case.

00:01:39.441 --> 00:01:40.900
Essentially, playing
and maximizing

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:43.960
expected number of chips is
a pretty good approximation

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:45.790
of how you actually
should be playing.

00:01:45.790 --> 00:01:47.980
But there are some
small differences

00:01:47.980 --> 00:01:49.900
in extreme situations,
and I'd like

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:51.680
to highlight some of that today.

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:53.800
So OK, yeah.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:56.770
So this is essentially-- so it's
this idea of minimizing risk

00:01:56.770 --> 00:02:00.640
to stay alive and move up
to the escalating payouts.

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:02.980
So I want to make an
important distinction, though.

00:02:02.980 --> 00:02:05.170
When I'm saying,
we're still trying

00:02:05.170 --> 00:02:07.840
to maximize our expected
amount of money.

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:10.780
What I'm saying, you should
be minimizing your risk

00:02:10.780 --> 00:02:13.690
in a tournament so that you
can move up the payouts.

00:02:13.690 --> 00:02:17.500
That's different than
saying you should minimize

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:20.020
your monetary risk
because I'm still

00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:23.680
assuming we're trying to
maximize our expected money

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:24.970
without worrying about risk.

00:02:24.970 --> 00:02:28.090
But we're only minimizing
tournament risk

00:02:28.090 --> 00:02:30.520
to maximize your
expected amount of money.

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:32.680
But I'm not saying
we should be overly

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:35.080
conservative in a
tournament and just

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:37.360
trying to move up the
money ladder slowly

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:41.110
when you should be gambling
because it's positive money

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:42.250
expectation.

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:43.930
If you find yourself
in this situation,

00:02:43.930 --> 00:02:47.260
then if you're trying to
play professionally and just

00:02:47.260 --> 00:02:49.840
maximize your expected amount
of money in every situation,

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:51.970
then you should probably
play smaller tournaments,

00:02:51.970 --> 00:02:53.535
where this is not
really the case--

00:02:53.535 --> 00:02:55.950
where this doesn't
occur too often.

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:58.570
I can understand in practice,
if you play poker for fun

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:00.280
and you made it
far in a tournament

00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:04.120
and it's the top,
let's say, 50K,

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:07.810
and there's 55 left, I can
understand why you might not

00:03:07.810 --> 00:03:15.120
want to make a positive money
expectation play because you've

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:16.170
played this tournament.

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:18.170
You're probably not going
to be in the situation

00:03:18.170 --> 00:03:19.930
that many times
in your lifetime.

00:03:19.930 --> 00:03:22.000
And you just really
want to cash the World

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.666
Series of Poker main
event or something.

00:03:23.666 --> 00:03:25.750
And I think that's a
reasonable life decision.

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:27.625
I'm not criticizing
that life decision.

00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:33.365
But I'm going to talk about
all of these decisions

00:03:33.365 --> 00:03:35.200
assuming we don't
care about that.

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:38.290
We're still trying to maximize
expected amount of money.

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:39.880
And if you are playing
professionally,

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:42.800
where you're getting into that
situation very frequently,

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:46.690
then it is very important to
maximize risk in some cases

00:03:46.690 --> 00:03:51.640
and to maximize your dollar EV
because in tournaments, you're

00:03:51.640 --> 00:03:52.820
losing most of the time.

00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:58.060
You really have to win a lot
the times that you do win.

00:03:58.060 --> 00:04:03.360
You can't be content
because we made $30,000

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:05.710
if we could have made $50,000.

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:07.379
So OK.

00:04:07.379 --> 00:04:09.670
So what is the exact formula
for ICM/ So I'm just going

00:04:09.670 --> 00:04:13.240
to demonstrate how to
calculate the value of chips

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:15.980
in a tournament with an example.

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:19.149
So ICM is essentially
a formula to calculate

00:04:19.149 --> 00:04:21.279
how much your stack is
worth in a tournament.

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:23.620
So let's suppose there's
three players left

00:04:23.620 --> 00:04:25.480
and that payouts are 5, 3, 2.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:27.240
This is a common
structure in sit-and-goes

00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:30.425
if you've played those, which
are 10-player tournaments.

00:04:30.425 --> 00:04:32.050
So this is the
statement is essentially

00:04:32.050 --> 00:04:34.060
your chances of winning
the tournament is

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:36.850
proportional to your
percent of the total chips.

00:04:36.850 --> 00:04:39.570
And essentially we're
assuming this is true,

00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:43.510
and we're going to derive
from it all the formulas.

00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:45.250
And this statement is
approximately true.

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:47.800
There are more advanced
ICM calculators

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:49.900
that also take into
account your position

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:53.050
if the stack sizes are rather
shallow because there are

00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:55.570
some inaccuracies
because this statement,

00:04:55.570 --> 00:04:57.520
it calculates only
based on chips.

00:04:57.520 --> 00:04:59.560
But if you're folding
and then you're

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:02.110
the button the next hand,
which is the best position,

00:05:02.110 --> 00:05:05.400
then that's actually
an entire big blind

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:07.954
better almost than being
under the gun the next hand.

00:05:07.954 --> 00:05:09.620
But we're not going
to worry about that.

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:11.410
We're just going to
assume your chances

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:13.910
of winning the tournament is
proportional to your percentage

00:05:13.910 --> 00:05:14.440
of chips.

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:17.470
So how do we calculate this?

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:20.380
So you can't really do
it by hand in practice.

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:23.070
But for this example
with three people,

00:05:23.070 --> 00:05:24.900
I'll show you how
to do it by hand.

00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:27.440
So let's suppose the chips
stacks are also 5, 3, 2.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:29.480
OK, so the payouts are 5, 3, 2.

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:33.110
And the chip stacks
are also 5, 3, 2 ratio.

00:05:33.110 --> 00:05:36.900
If chip EV equals money EV,
then the guy with 5,000,

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:40.160
their equity from the
tournament should be $5.

00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:41.990
And the guy in third
place, their equity

00:05:41.990 --> 00:05:43.370
should be $2, right?

00:05:43.370 --> 00:05:46.750
But this is clearly not correct
because the guy in third place

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:48.170
is guaranteed $2.

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:49.699
And clearly there's
a nonzero chance

00:05:49.699 --> 00:05:50.990
of them winning the tournament.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:54.050
So clearly their equity
is actually more than $2.

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:56.270
And then similarly
if you're player A,

00:05:56.270 --> 00:05:59.450
your equity is clearly not $5
because you're not guaranteed

00:05:59.450 --> 00:06:00.950
to win the tournament.

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:04.130
So it's clear from this
example why if you just do chip

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:07.110
EV equals money EV,
that's clearly wrong.

00:06:07.110 --> 00:06:10.040
Is that clear to everyone?

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:11.900
So how do we calculate it?

00:06:11.900 --> 00:06:13.595
So let's calculate
it for player C.

00:06:13.595 --> 00:06:15.470
So essentially what it's
saying, your chances

00:06:15.470 --> 00:06:17.700
of winning, your
chances of coming first

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:21.290
is 2,000 over
10,000, which is 20%.

00:06:21.290 --> 00:06:23.530
And then to calculate your
chances of coming second,

00:06:23.530 --> 00:06:26.930
you just condition on each
of the other player's way.

00:06:26.930 --> 00:06:28.580
So conditioned on
A winning, which

00:06:28.580 --> 00:06:30.566
would happen 50% of
the time, we assume

00:06:30.566 --> 00:06:31.940
that our chances
of coming second

00:06:31.940 --> 00:06:36.529
is 2,000 divided by 5,000,
which is the remaining

00:06:36.529 --> 00:06:38.820
number of chips besides player
A. Does that make sense?

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:40.670
So player A has 5,000 chips.

00:06:40.670 --> 00:06:45.310
So between you who's
player C and player D,

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:48.320
there's 5,000 chips in total,
and you got 2,000 of those.

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:51.680
So it's 2,000 over
5,000, so it's 0.4.

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:54.350
And then if player B wins, then
your chances of coming second

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:56.210
is 2,000 over 7,000.

00:06:56.210 --> 00:07:00.520
So overall, your chances
of coming second is 0.4--

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:07.820
So it says, 50% times
0.4 plus 30% times 2/7,

00:07:07.820 --> 00:07:09.470
which equals 2/7.

00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:11.300
So then you can
calculate your equity

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:12.830
is-- you're guaranteed $2.

00:07:12.830 --> 00:07:15.600
And you have a 20% chance of
winning, which would give you

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:17.000
three additional dollars.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.550
And then a 29% chance of coming
second, which would give you

00:07:19.550 --> 00:07:20.750
an additional dollar.

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:23.870
So your equity is actually
2.89 in this case.

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:28.522
is actually closer to second
place than third place.

00:07:28.522 --> 00:07:30.600
Does that calculation
make sense to everyone?

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:33.220
So if there's five
players, you just

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:34.820
have to recursively condition.

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:37.160
You have to condition on
player A winning and then

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:39.500
go through all the possibilities
of who can come second.

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:40.880
Then go through all
the possibilities

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:42.838
of who could comes third,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:07:42.838 --> 00:07:46.760
So it's not a calculation you
can really do in your head.

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:51.300
But that it's quite easy to find
a calculator to do it for you.

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:54.110
You just Google ICM calculator,
and you punch it in.

00:07:54.110 --> 00:07:55.910
And even though it's not--

00:07:55.910 --> 00:07:57.080
it grows exponentially.

00:07:57.080 --> 00:07:59.990
But there's only going
to be nine players.

00:07:59.990 --> 00:08:01.300
So it's still fine.

00:08:01.300 --> 00:08:02.246
It won't take that--

00:08:02.246 --> 00:08:03.620
the computer can
do it instantly,

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:07.550
even for 9-10 players.

00:08:07.550 --> 00:08:12.780
OK, so what are some cases
where ICM is easy to calculate?

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:16.730
So like I said, in cash games,
there is no such thing as ICM.

00:08:16.730 --> 00:08:19.400
You're just playing to maximize
expected number of chips.

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:21.890
And your goal is
essentially, you're

00:08:21.890 --> 00:08:25.650
sitting out at the cash game
looking to get into all-ins,

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:27.380
looking to get into
favorable all-ins,

00:08:27.380 --> 00:08:32.510
hopefully winning the person
who you're targeting's money.

00:08:32.510 --> 00:08:34.450
And in winner-takes-all
tournaments,

00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:37.277
it's also the same
because you're just

00:08:37.277 --> 00:08:39.360
looking at your chances
of winning the tournament.

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:41.260
And that's always just
your number of chips.

00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:42.634
So you're just
trying to maximize

00:08:42.634 --> 00:08:44.690
expected number of chips.

00:08:44.690 --> 00:08:47.120
So as a corollary, once it
gets down to two players,

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:49.660
there's no more
such thing as ICM.

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:51.835
Three is the minimum
number of players you

00:08:51.835 --> 00:08:53.600
need for ICM to be relevant.

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:56.840
Once it's two players, it's
just maximize your chip EV

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:00.390
because there's no sense of
trying to survive in hopes

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:01.950
that someone else busts first.

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:04.850
Because with only two people,
for the other guy to bust,

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:06.380
you have to take
all their chips.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:12.010
OK, so what are some
mathematical corollaries

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:14.260
of ICM formula?

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:17.380
So big stacks have money
EV less than chip EV.

00:09:17.380 --> 00:09:21.240
Small stacks have money
EV greater than chip EV.

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:24.432
Small stacks also tend to have
positive chip EV in general.

00:09:24.432 --> 00:09:26.390
This is something I didn't
mention to you much.

00:09:26.390 --> 00:09:28.740
But in general-- so you
might have seen this

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:31.900
if you guys have been to a
casino and played cash games.

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:35.620
So let's say you sit down
at a table in a cash game

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:38.710
and everyone buys in
for 100 big blinds.

00:09:38.710 --> 00:09:41.020
At some tables, usually
they'll allow you to buy in

00:09:41.020 --> 00:09:43.490
for as low as 20 big blinds.

00:09:43.490 --> 00:09:46.300
And if you do this,
in general, that's

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:50.590
going to be positive EV for
the guy with 20 big blinds

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:54.560
because there's situations
where they have to--

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:57.940
Where, let's say, they have
to essentially sometimes

00:09:57.940 --> 00:09:58.960
one guy will raise.

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:00.040
One guy will call.

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:01.510
And then you can go all in.

00:10:01.510 --> 00:10:04.210
And one guy will go
all in on top of you.

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:05.500
And the other guy will fold.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:08.500
And then you have dead money.

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:11.230
So another thing is early
on in the tournament,

00:10:11.230 --> 00:10:12.454
ICM is irrelevant.

00:10:12.454 --> 00:10:13.870
You just want to
accumulate chips.

00:10:13.870 --> 00:10:18.160
So if you try to do this formula
early on in a tournament, what

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:23.050
you'll find is
essentially you're

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:25.660
so far away from the money
that none of the things

00:10:25.660 --> 00:10:27.790
really matter to maximize
your chances of even

00:10:27.790 --> 00:10:28.960
getting to the money.

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:32.440
You just want to maximize
your number of chips.

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:33.830
So where is ICM most relevant?

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:36.340
It's most relevant on
the exact payout bubble

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:38.240
and on the final table.

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:40.600
So roughly speaking, in
every poker tournament

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:43.680
I've seen other than strange
ones that are winner-takes-all

00:10:43.680 --> 00:10:48.020
or satellites, the payout
looks roughly like this.

00:10:48.020 --> 00:10:49.240
So it's 0.

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:53.560
You go in, and once you hit
about top 20% is the bubble.

00:10:53.560 --> 00:10:58.180
And then there's a jump here
where suddenly you get paid.

00:10:58.180 --> 00:11:01.430
This is about 80% get 0.

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:03.290
So here there's a
jump, and then it

00:11:03.290 --> 00:11:07.195
escalates slowly until you
get to the final table.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:13.420
Final-- sorry, I'll
actually switched to color--

00:11:13.420 --> 00:11:14.650
final table.

00:11:14.650 --> 00:11:16.780
And then it escalates
really fast.

00:11:16.780 --> 00:11:20.170
So essentially basically ICM
is most relevant at the points

00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:22.160
where essentially,
the derivative,

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:25.040
or the rate of change
the payout, is highest.

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:28.480
And those points, as you
can see, are here and here.

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:32.850
So essentially it matters
most at the exact money bubble

00:11:32.850 --> 00:11:36.280
and in the final table.

00:11:36.280 --> 00:11:37.495
OK, let me clear this.

00:11:40.670 --> 00:11:42.200
OK, so yeah, so
some more extreme

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:44.960
examples of ICM
you have one chip

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:47.060
left late in the tournament
when everyone else

00:11:47.060 --> 00:11:48.200
has thousands of chips.

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:49.970
So clearly this ship
is worth a lot more

00:11:49.970 --> 00:11:52.190
than its value as a
fraction of the chips.

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:54.410
And you're just trying to
survive with this one chip

00:11:54.410 --> 00:11:56.690
essentially instead of
trying to win more chips.

00:12:00.002 --> 00:12:01.460
Maybe I'll calculate
this in a bit.

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:03.507
So in satellites--
what satellites are

00:12:03.507 --> 00:12:05.090
are there are
tournaments where you're

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:07.430
trying to qualify for
a bigger tournament.

00:12:07.430 --> 00:12:09.380
So essentially the
important thing

00:12:09.380 --> 00:12:12.020
is there will be
maybe 100 players.

00:12:12.020 --> 00:12:13.430
And there will be
10 seats, which

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:16.560
means the top 10 get an invite
to the bigger tournament.

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:18.110
And then everyone
else gets nothing.

00:12:18.110 --> 00:12:21.320
So I guess the qualifiers for
the MIT Series of Poker Main

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:23.846
Event are kind of like this.

00:12:23.846 --> 00:12:25.220
I guess there's
other prizes, to.

00:12:25.220 --> 00:12:27.094
But you're essentially
trying to come top 10.

00:12:27.094 --> 00:12:29.330
So this is how that works.

00:12:29.330 --> 00:12:33.860
And in that case, the
payout is essentially this.

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:36.300
So there's not really
much incentive to win.

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:40.970
You're just trying to be one
of this top 10% that gets paid.

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:44.210
So that's another case where
ICM has extreme importance.

00:12:44.210 --> 00:12:45.220
And you often find--

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:47.300
well, not often--
but you can often

00:12:47.300 --> 00:12:50.620
make a case for folding
pocket aces preflop

00:12:50.620 --> 00:12:52.830
even though you know it's
going to have positive chip

00:12:52.830 --> 00:12:56.030
EV if you call because it's
the best possible hand.

00:12:56.030 --> 00:12:59.310
But because you just really
don't want to bust, then

00:12:59.310 --> 00:13:01.610
just you want to fold aces.

00:13:01.610 --> 00:13:05.014
OK, we'll talk about
this a bit more later.

