00:22:29.730 --> 00:22:32.070
He's not going to fold
ace-queen if I go all in.

00:22:32.070 --> 00:22:34.140
So I just give this one to him.

00:22:37.050 --> 00:22:39.510
Calling is probably bad
anyway, but calling, I think,

00:22:39.510 --> 00:22:41.310
is especially bad
because it just

00:22:41.310 --> 00:22:44.780
increases the chances of
getting in a bigger pot.

00:22:47.881 --> 00:22:49.357
OK, we'll skip forward a bit.

00:22:49.357 --> 00:22:50.190
Let's see this hand.

00:22:53.100 --> 00:22:54.340
So ace-10 off here.

00:22:54.340 --> 00:22:56.460
So this guy makes it 12,000.

00:22:56.460 --> 00:22:59.100
And I guess I've skipped
a bunch of hands.

00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:01.890
So Nicholas Brody, I think,
has been very active.

00:23:01.890 --> 00:23:04.960
And overall, I think people
have become very active.

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:06.540
Everyone's playing
a lot of pots.

00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:10.380
So overall, I am going to
put people on wider ranges

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:12.780
than I normally do.

00:23:12.780 --> 00:23:15.900
But nonetheless here,
I still fold ace-10.

00:23:15.900 --> 00:23:18.810
I think it's ace-jack I
would probably get it in.

00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:22.080
And ace-10 suited, I
think I'd get it in.

00:23:22.080 --> 00:23:25.290
Ace-10 suited is borderline.

00:23:25.290 --> 00:23:30.330
Once again, when you're tied
between getting in a smaller

00:23:30.330 --> 00:23:36.030
pot and getting in a bigger
pot, you want to be folding.

00:23:36.030 --> 00:23:37.447
Yeah, so I guess
at a final table,

00:23:37.447 --> 00:23:38.488
I should make this clear.

00:23:38.488 --> 00:23:40.020
It's not like you
want to fold more.

00:23:40.020 --> 00:23:43.540
It's you want to go all in
more when you're first to act.

00:23:43.540 --> 00:23:45.956
But call other
people's all-ins less.

00:23:45.956 --> 00:23:47.580
So that's exactly
what's going on here.

00:23:47.580 --> 00:23:49.200
He's already moved all in.

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:51.920
And I'm going to
fold to his all-in

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:53.980
more often than
in a normal game.

00:23:53.980 --> 00:23:56.250
But as you can see,
I haven't really

00:23:56.250 --> 00:23:59.350
been tighter in every sense
because when I get to go first,

00:23:59.350 --> 00:24:02.310
I think actually going all
in more often and risking it

00:24:02.310 --> 00:24:04.620
more often because I
know my opponents are

00:24:04.620 --> 00:24:08.161
highly incentivized to fold.

00:24:08.161 --> 00:24:08.910
So they go all in.

00:24:08.910 --> 00:24:10.020
I fold here.

00:24:10.020 --> 00:24:12.880
So Nicholas Brody also
folds, which I guess is fine.

00:24:15.214 --> 00:24:17.130
Definitely he had pretty
odds he called there.

00:24:20.310 --> 00:24:22.520
But once again, ICM just makes--

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:24.220
it changes things up a bit.

00:24:24.220 --> 00:24:26.340
Jack-7 suited, once again,
is a pretty big shove,

00:24:26.340 --> 00:24:29.099
but jack-7 suited plenty
good [INAUDIBLE]----

00:24:29.099 --> 00:24:29.640
ICM relevant.

00:24:32.200 --> 00:24:33.720
Pocket 9s here.

00:24:33.720 --> 00:24:36.750
We make it 12,000 on the button.

00:24:36.750 --> 00:24:39.090
So here I think pocket
9s is good enough

00:24:39.090 --> 00:24:42.300
where I'm happy if one of them
reraises all-in, and I call.

00:24:42.300 --> 00:24:44.340
So essentially my
strategy here is

00:24:44.340 --> 00:24:47.520
I'm going to shove all
my medium strength hands

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:49.020
and especially hands
that don't play

00:24:49.020 --> 00:24:51.900
well postflop ace-2 offsuit.

00:24:51.900 --> 00:24:55.320
And then I'm going to raise
small with some of my hands

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:58.140
that are less good preflop but
better postflop, let's say,

00:24:58.140 --> 00:25:02.910
10-8 suited, and also my
monster hands like pocket nines

00:25:02.910 --> 00:25:05.250
that are also reasonable
to play postflop.

00:25:07.990 --> 00:25:10.140
So Nicholas Brody calls here.

00:25:10.140 --> 00:25:13.350
And the flop is ace,
jack, 7 with the hearts.

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:15.120
So it's a bad flop
for our hand, but it's

00:25:15.120 --> 00:25:19.020
a good flop for
our range because I

00:25:19.020 --> 00:25:22.300
think, given the way the table
was going, I was opening a lot.

00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:24.930
And Nicholas Brody
is very aggressive.

00:25:24.930 --> 00:25:26.620
I would guess unless
he had like pocket

00:25:26.620 --> 00:25:31.670
aces, which he might slow
play, he would reraise most.

00:25:31.670 --> 00:25:35.180
I wasn't 100% sure-confident,
but I was reasonable--

00:25:35.180 --> 00:25:39.770
I'd say maybe 85% confident
that if he had an ace preflop,

00:25:39.770 --> 00:25:41.760
he would have just
went all in preflop.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:44.781
So overall, I'd still say it's
a very good flop for my range

00:25:44.781 --> 00:25:47.280
because I think he's way less
likely to have an ace than me.

00:25:47.280 --> 00:25:49.680
There's a small
chance maybe he would

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:53.030
chicken out with ace-2
offsuit and just call.

00:25:53.030 --> 00:25:54.660
But given how
aggressive he's been,

00:25:54.660 --> 00:25:57.220
I would be surprised
if he did that.

00:25:57.220 --> 00:25:58.770
So I decided to bet here.

00:25:58.770 --> 00:26:01.590
And I'm still not sure
how good this bet is.

00:26:01.590 --> 00:26:04.060
So I think at the
time I bet, because

00:26:04.060 --> 00:26:07.620
of my logic that it's really
hard for him to have an ace,

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:10.230
and so I think the best
strategy for me on this flop

00:26:10.230 --> 00:26:14.190
and in this situation is to
just bet 100% of my hands.

00:26:14.190 --> 00:26:16.860
And he's just forced
to fold basically

00:26:16.860 --> 00:26:19.660
very often because he can't
really keep up with an ace.

00:26:19.660 --> 00:26:22.020
I can just continue betting.

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:24.060
That being said,
though, I do think

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:26.550
if I do decide as
part of my strategy

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:28.530
to check any part
of my range here,

00:26:28.530 --> 00:26:31.680
pocket 9s might actually be
one of the best possible hands

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:32.410
to check back.

00:26:32.410 --> 00:26:34.530
So I think checking back
would have been fine.

00:26:34.530 --> 00:26:36.870
I guess I'd bet here
because I told myself,

00:26:36.870 --> 00:26:40.680
I want my strategy to be bet
100% of my hands, which I did.

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:46.200
And he folds, which is
reasonably smart because he

00:26:46.200 --> 00:26:47.710
knows that I can bet again.

00:26:47.710 --> 00:26:50.340
And he's going to have to make
a decision for all his chips

00:26:50.340 --> 00:26:50.940
probably.

00:26:50.940 --> 00:26:52.273
And it's just going to be tough.

00:26:55.870 --> 00:26:57.680
OK, this hand--

00:26:57.680 --> 00:27:01.881
BeMySponsor goes all
in, gets [INAUDIBLE]..

00:27:05.318 --> 00:27:07.330
Yeah?

00:27:07.330 --> 00:27:10.645
AUDIENCE: Why would you say,
pocket 9s is one of the best

00:27:10.645 --> 00:27:11.760
hands to check back here?

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:19.040
WILL MA: I very rarely
get called by worse,

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:20.980
and I get called by
everything better.

00:27:20.980 --> 00:27:24.680
I think he's always calling a
jack and usually folding a 7.

00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:27.050
Maybe he won't fold 7-8
with some back door draws,

00:27:27.050 --> 00:27:29.295
but I think he'll
usually call a jack.

00:27:29.295 --> 00:27:31.020
And maybe he'll
call a 7 sometimes.

00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:33.670
But I still think mostly
it's just he'll basically

00:27:33.670 --> 00:27:36.055
fold everything that beats
me and call everything that--

00:27:36.055 --> 00:27:39.010
sorry, he'll fold everything
that I beat and call everything

00:27:39.010 --> 00:27:40.672
that beats me basically.

00:27:43.390 --> 00:27:46.630
Yeah, but I still decide
to bet, nonetheless, just

00:27:46.630 --> 00:27:48.310
to win the pot there
and not give him

00:27:48.310 --> 00:27:52.037
extra outs if he happens to
have 10-6 suited or something.

00:27:54.719 --> 00:27:56.260
So OK, so we'll go
through this hand.

00:27:56.260 --> 00:27:57.640
So Panpancrisy raises.

00:27:57.640 --> 00:27:59.940
He doesn't go all
in, which is curious.

00:27:59.940 --> 00:28:02.230
But LPMBox calls.

00:28:02.230 --> 00:28:03.430
He calls again.

00:28:03.430 --> 00:28:04.700
It's checked.

00:28:04.700 --> 00:28:08.257
And then LPMBox goes on
in the river [INAUDIBLE]..

00:28:11.530 --> 00:28:13.300
OK, jack-7 here?

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:14.094
Yes.

00:28:14.094 --> 00:28:16.010
I guess, so once again,
Nicholas Brady raises.

00:28:16.010 --> 00:28:20.290
And then LPMBox goes on
over him, wins a big pot.

00:28:23.380 --> 00:28:25.810
So I guess I do the
same for Nicholas Brady.

00:28:25.810 --> 00:28:29.290
He's been raising a lot,
so pockets 6s good enough

00:28:29.290 --> 00:28:30.700
to risk going all in there.

00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:37.120
OK, this hand-- so we
get ace-jack suited.

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:40.720
And I raise from cutoff.

00:28:40.720 --> 00:28:43.270
So I've been raising
to a fairly small size

00:28:43.270 --> 00:28:44.700
because the antes are smaller.

00:28:44.700 --> 00:28:47.290
So that's one thing to
remember at a final table is

00:28:47.290 --> 00:28:50.140
the pots are actually a bit
smaller because with only five

00:28:50.140 --> 00:28:53.680
players the ante, the sum of
the antes, instead of normally

00:28:53.680 --> 00:28:56.530
the 6,000, is only
3,000 in this case.

00:28:56.530 --> 00:29:00.080
So the big blind has
worse odds to call.

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:01.860
So Nicholas Brady goes all in.

00:29:01.860 --> 00:29:03.940
I look him up ace-jack suited--

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:05.320
definitely good enough.

00:29:05.320 --> 00:29:07.810
Also at this point,
because a number of pots

00:29:07.810 --> 00:29:11.500
have gone my way, I'm big enough
where even if I call and lose

00:29:11.500 --> 00:29:15.730
this, I won't be chip
leader, but I'll still

00:29:15.730 --> 00:29:18.550
have a decent amount of chips.

00:29:18.550 --> 00:29:20.810
So unfortunately we
lose the ace-8 here.

00:29:20.810 --> 00:29:22.750
So now we're second
place, but we're still

00:29:22.750 --> 00:29:23.800
doing reasonably well.

00:29:29.770 --> 00:29:31.661
I could just maybe
gone all in here.

00:29:31.661 --> 00:29:33.160
I guess this guy
has a lot of chips.

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:35.650
But I could've raised
to a bigger size

00:29:35.650 --> 00:29:38.530
to disincentive Nicholas
Brody from doing this

00:29:38.530 --> 00:29:40.030
with the right
wide range of hands

00:29:40.030 --> 00:29:44.050
and then protecting my stack
more from an ICM point of view.

00:29:44.050 --> 00:29:45.310
But I'm happy with--

00:29:45.310 --> 00:29:47.200
I think ace-jack suited
is just good enough

00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:50.147
where I'm happy
calling his all-in,

00:29:50.147 --> 00:29:51.730
which I should have
been in this case.

00:29:51.730 --> 00:29:52.820
I guess he had ace-6.

00:29:57.160 --> 00:30:00.270
OK, so jack-10 suited here.

00:30:00.270 --> 00:30:04.120
So yeah, here I just
decided to fold.

00:30:04.120 --> 00:30:06.680
I mean we could consider
doing a crazy bluff all-in,

00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:10.160
but I don't think this
guy's folding that often.

00:30:10.160 --> 00:30:13.760
They made a rather
big reraise preflop

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:18.492
from going three times
the initial opening.

00:30:18.492 --> 00:30:21.830
So Nicholas Brody goes all
in here, and they do fold.

00:30:21.830 --> 00:30:23.860
So Nicholas Brody picking
up a bunch of chips.

00:30:27.264 --> 00:30:28.555
So he just takes it down again.

00:30:28.555 --> 00:30:29.850
He's been raising quite a lot.

00:30:37.990 --> 00:30:39.400
Here we get a raise and a call.

00:30:39.400 --> 00:30:45.950
So LPMBox has been raising
over other people's--

00:30:45.950 --> 00:30:47.020
opens quite a lot.

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:49.490
So he gets called here,
but he holds and wins,

00:30:49.490 --> 00:30:52.270
which is definitely
bad news for everyone.

00:30:52.270 --> 00:30:56.110
If I could pay 10,000
chips into the pot

00:30:56.110 --> 00:30:58.024
to have this all-in
go the other way,

00:30:58.024 --> 00:30:59.690
it almost certainly
would be profitable.

00:30:59.690 --> 00:31:01.439
The amount actually
we'd be willing to pay

00:31:01.439 --> 00:31:05.810
you make this all-in go the
other way is probably 25,000.

00:31:05.810 --> 00:31:08.590
It's a ridiculous amount
because just the value

00:31:08.590 --> 00:31:10.780
of having people bust
and moving up the payouts

00:31:10.780 --> 00:31:13.420
is so significant,
especially when I'm

00:31:13.420 --> 00:31:15.196
not such a big stack anymore.

00:31:18.390 --> 00:31:22.300
OK, so now this guy,
he just doubled up.

00:31:22.300 --> 00:31:24.010
So I guess we were
running pretty good.

00:31:24.010 --> 00:31:26.857
But I'd say in the last two or
three orbits, as you can see,

00:31:26.857 --> 00:31:28.690
a lot of things haven't
been that favorable.

00:31:28.690 --> 00:31:30.220
We've lost some all-ins.

00:31:30.220 --> 00:31:32.710
And also people
haven't really busted.

00:31:32.710 --> 00:31:35.620
The chips are just being
passed around the table, which

00:31:35.620 --> 00:31:39.130
is basically not what
you're hoping for.

00:31:42.730 --> 00:31:44.090
So king-10 offsuit.

00:31:44.090 --> 00:31:45.134
We get a walk.

00:31:45.134 --> 00:31:47.050
So walk just means that
everyone folds to you,

00:31:47.050 --> 00:31:48.000
and the big blind.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:50.550
I think we've actually
gotten quite a lot of walks

00:31:50.550 --> 00:31:52.380
at this final table.

00:31:52.380 --> 00:31:54.150
So something we can
keep in mind if we're

00:31:54.150 --> 00:31:58.855
trying to play exploitatively
later, queen-jack, go all in.

00:31:58.855 --> 00:31:59.355
He folds.

00:32:02.950 --> 00:32:07.190
So at 8-7 I guess, LPMBox, after
winning that, so as you notice,

00:32:07.190 --> 00:32:09.810
the big stacks are the ones
who win most of the pots.

00:32:09.810 --> 00:32:11.390
And this is expected.

00:32:11.390 --> 00:32:15.470
So whenever ICM is relevant,
you would expect that--

00:32:15.470 --> 00:32:19.730
so although the small stacks had
a higher chip EV, then-- sorry,

00:32:19.730 --> 00:32:22.430
had a higher money
EV than chip EV,

00:32:22.430 --> 00:32:24.687
usually the chips
get transferred

00:32:24.687 --> 00:32:26.270
from the small stack
to the big stacks

00:32:26.270 --> 00:32:28.670
because the big stacks
have more license

00:32:28.670 --> 00:32:34.040
to go all in first and
bully people around.

00:32:34.040 --> 00:32:37.520
So he takes this one down.

00:32:37.520 --> 00:32:39.530
Next hand, we get jacks here.

00:32:39.530 --> 00:32:41.600
So Panpancrisy is
actually short now even

00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:43.950
though he started the final
table as the chip leader

00:32:43.950 --> 00:32:45.980
because he's lost
a bunch of all-ins.

00:32:45.980 --> 00:32:48.890
He gets an all-in here,
and we hold against a 6.

00:32:51.670 --> 00:32:53.800
So there's actually an
interesting play here.

00:32:53.800 --> 00:32:55.370
I don't think he
should have done it.

00:32:55.370 --> 00:32:58.330
But this is actually
often a good ICM play.

00:32:58.330 --> 00:33:02.157
So normally I would
say in this situation,

00:33:02.157 --> 00:33:04.240
if you have a good hand,
just go all in because he

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:05.470
knows I'm going to call.

00:33:05.470 --> 00:33:07.450
So when ace-6, he
just went all in.

00:33:07.450 --> 00:33:11.110
But often there's this play
called the stop-and-go, which

00:33:11.110 --> 00:33:12.597
is in practice not very good.

00:33:12.597 --> 00:33:14.180
I don't think it
would have been here,

00:33:14.180 --> 00:33:16.060
but it's an interesting
theoretical concept,

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:19.570
which is instead of going
on, he just calls, OK?

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:22.780
He calls, and then
he basically blindly

00:33:22.780 --> 00:33:25.140
goes all in on the flop.

00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:26.950
He doesn't actually
have to, but this

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:28.144
is what players used to do.

00:33:28.144 --> 00:33:29.560
And you can do
this in live poker.

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:31.143
What you would do
in this situation is

00:33:31.143 --> 00:33:34.020
you would say, call, and before
the dealer even deals the flop,

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:35.380
you would just say, all in.

00:33:35.380 --> 00:33:36.760
And this is a legal play.

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:42.600
The point is
essentially-- it's an ICM.

00:33:42.600 --> 00:33:45.340
The justification, which I
think is mostly wrong but still

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:50.770
interesting, is he
wants to maximize

00:33:50.770 --> 00:33:52.150
the chances that I fold.

00:33:52.150 --> 00:33:54.500
So essentially, OK, this
is strictly better, right?

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:59.170
Sorry, the fact that he would
call, let me see the flop,

00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:01.570
and then I get to decide
whether to put the remaining

00:34:01.570 --> 00:34:04.600
chips in sounds like it
should be better for me

00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:07.120
than me having to put
all the chips in preflop.

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:08.620
But the main reason
why he does this

00:34:08.620 --> 00:34:13.420
is because he wants me to have
an opportunity to fold my cards

00:34:13.420 --> 00:34:15.940
and avoid getting in a
situation where both of us

00:34:15.940 --> 00:34:18.290
are playing for
our entire stack.

00:34:18.290 --> 00:34:20.639
So this is the
justification for it.

00:34:20.639 --> 00:34:23.590
So even though you're giving
your opponent more information,

00:34:23.590 --> 00:34:25.210
you're also
decreasing the chances

00:34:25.210 --> 00:34:27.670
that they decide to
call to the river card

00:34:27.670 --> 00:34:30.370
and have more chances
of beating you.

00:34:30.370 --> 00:34:32.510
So that justification
is correct,

00:34:32.510 --> 00:34:34.600
but it's just that if
you've crunched the numbers,

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:37.330
usually this situation
won't be favorable enough.

00:34:37.330 --> 00:34:39.730
And usually you don't want
to be giving your opponent

00:34:39.730 --> 00:34:42.820
that extra information.

00:34:42.820 --> 00:34:44.965
OK, so finally someone busts.

00:34:48.166 --> 00:34:49.860
We get jacks off again.

00:34:49.860 --> 00:34:53.520
So here normally I think I would
often consider calling this,

00:34:53.520 --> 00:34:56.530
but I think just avoid-- so
now the stacks are even--

00:34:56.530 --> 00:34:58.770
we're the chip leader
but not by a ton--

00:34:58.770 --> 00:35:01.620
and I don't really want
to get in a big pot here.

00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:04.156
So I decide to give it to
them, even though normally I

00:35:04.156 --> 00:35:05.280
would definitely call this.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:10.200
King-7 suited.

00:35:10.200 --> 00:35:12.660
I make a pretty big
all-in for 21 and 1/2 bets

00:35:12.660 --> 00:35:14.090
from the small blind.

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:15.180
And take it down.

00:35:19.810 --> 00:35:23.760
All right, we'll
see all the hands.

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:26.220
We fold 6-3 suited here.

00:35:26.220 --> 00:35:28.890
BeMySponsor decided
to raise small, which

00:35:28.890 --> 00:35:30.340
is, once again, a bit unusual.

00:35:30.340 --> 00:35:33.030
You usually just want to go
all in in a situation where

00:35:33.030 --> 00:35:35.000
ICM is so relevant.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:36.250
And then Nicholas goes all in.

00:35:36.250 --> 00:35:37.040
And he folds.

00:35:43.170 --> 00:35:44.220
Jack-5 offsuit.

00:35:44.220 --> 00:35:45.439
Here we fold.

00:35:45.439 --> 00:35:46.980
So once again, this
guy raises small.

00:35:46.980 --> 00:35:50.940
So maybe he doesn't really
want to do this ICM thing

00:35:50.940 --> 00:35:53.799
and just he wants to play pots.

00:35:53.799 --> 00:35:55.090
He takes that one down, though.

00:35:58.381 --> 00:36:00.630
Nicholas Brody-- so as you
can see, it's a bit boring.

00:36:00.630 --> 00:36:01.963
There's not too many hands here.

00:36:01.963 --> 00:36:06.330
That's what happens with there's
ICM because you don't really

00:36:06.330 --> 00:36:07.260
want to splash around.

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:09.390
You just want to survive
in the tournament

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:11.910
by risking all your
chips once in a while

00:36:11.910 --> 00:36:16.980
instead of slowly bleeding your
chips in a variety of pots.

00:36:16.980 --> 00:36:20.090
So once again, queen-9
suited, big all in.

00:36:20.090 --> 00:36:22.390
Plenty good enough.

00:36:22.390 --> 00:36:24.710
Queen-7 suited, I
decide to raise it up.

00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:28.770
But unfortunately, I guess, even
if just one guy went all in,

00:36:28.770 --> 00:36:30.210
I'm clearly folding.

00:36:30.210 --> 00:36:31.650
So they both go all in.

00:36:31.650 --> 00:36:35.340
And ace-king beats kings, which
