00:48:18.090 --> 00:48:22.320
in a satellite does not get
paid any more than 10th place.

00:48:22.320 --> 00:48:24.375
But in real tournaments,
you basically

00:48:24.375 --> 00:48:27.410
never fold aces
because even if you're

00:48:27.410 --> 00:48:30.040
risking losing all your
money, just first place

00:48:30.040 --> 00:48:32.150
will be hire than
second place by enough.

00:48:32.150 --> 00:48:34.830
And winning with those aces
will increases your chances

00:48:34.830 --> 00:48:38.740
of coming first by so much that
you should just gamble anyway.

00:48:38.740 --> 00:48:40.030
So this is only in satellites.

00:48:40.030 --> 00:48:44.479
Yeah, please don't fold aces in
like a normal poker tournament.

00:48:44.479 --> 00:48:44.978
Yeah?

00:48:44.978 --> 00:48:47.705
AUDIENCE: If you're a short
stack in a satellite or one

00:48:47.705 --> 00:48:51.120
of the shorter stacks, does
going all in still make sense?

00:48:51.120 --> 00:48:54.530
Because people can call you
without risking a tournament.

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:55.530
WILL MA: Right, exactly.

00:48:55.530 --> 00:48:58.380
So in that case, you actually
need a good had to go all in.

00:48:58.380 --> 00:49:00.250
You actually need to
have positive chip EV

00:49:00.250 --> 00:49:01.500
as well to go all in.

00:49:01.500 --> 00:49:05.440
Yeah, so that's why when ICM is
relevant, the small stacks win.

00:49:05.440 --> 00:49:07.322
And the big-- sorry,
the small stacks lose.

00:49:07.322 --> 00:49:08.280
And the big stacks win.

00:49:08.280 --> 00:49:10.140
Because the big stacks
have more license

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:14.850
to bully small sacks around,
whereas the small stacks can't

00:49:14.850 --> 00:49:16.995
because the big stacks can
call at them more often.

00:49:16.995 --> 00:49:20.250
AUDIENCE: And also does it
matter if other people have

00:49:20.250 --> 00:49:21.810
raised behind you?

00:49:21.810 --> 00:49:25.026
Does it just matter
who goes all in first?

00:49:25.026 --> 00:49:27.690
WILL MA: So if someone's
already raised,

00:49:27.690 --> 00:49:31.170
then it's more likely
you going all in--

00:49:31.170 --> 00:49:32.790
it's more likely
they are already

00:49:32.790 --> 00:49:35.920
committed so that if you
go all in, they won't fold.

00:49:35.920 --> 00:49:38.354
So that is relevant, yeah.

00:49:38.354 --> 00:49:41.470
OK, and cool.

00:49:41.470 --> 00:49:42.570
Right, so exactly.

00:49:42.570 --> 00:49:44.140
So in practice,
it's very tricky.

00:49:44.140 --> 00:49:45.515
And in fact, it
can be beneficial

00:49:45.515 --> 00:49:47.931
if you can somehow convince
your opponents that you're not

00:49:47.931 --> 00:49:48.570
rational.

00:49:48.570 --> 00:49:50.278
I've never personally
done this, but I've

00:49:50.278 --> 00:49:53.340
heard of people making a bad
call sometimes in a satellite

00:49:53.340 --> 00:49:56.600
just so people know not to
mess with him essentially.

00:49:56.600 --> 00:49:59.340
But I mean it's a bit weird.

00:49:59.340 --> 00:50:01.500
There is this weird
metagame with this traffic

00:50:01.500 --> 00:50:03.660
intersection-type
game, although this

00:50:03.660 --> 00:50:07.050
is only relevant in the most
extreme ICM situations, which

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:10.670
are satellites.

00:50:10.670 --> 00:50:12.570
Actually, I should
say, one scenario

00:50:12.570 --> 00:50:15.300
where I think you could
consider folding aces

00:50:15.300 --> 00:50:18.850
preflop in a normal
tournament is actually this.

00:50:18.850 --> 00:50:20.780
Let's say there's 55 until--

00:50:20.780 --> 00:50:23.070
let's say 54 get paid.

00:50:23.070 --> 00:50:24.290
And there's 55 left.

00:50:24.290 --> 00:50:26.045
And you've got one
chip, and everyone else

00:50:26.045 --> 00:50:27.440
has thousands of chips.

00:50:27.440 --> 00:50:29.754
And you know that
someone else has already

00:50:29.754 --> 00:50:30.920
gotten eliminated that hand.

00:50:30.920 --> 00:50:33.920
So if you fold, you're
guaranteed to get in the money.

00:50:33.920 --> 00:50:35.750
Then I would
definitely fold aces

00:50:35.750 --> 00:50:38.450
because even if you win in
double up, congratulations,

00:50:38.450 --> 00:50:40.790
you now have 10 chips
instead of one chip.

00:50:40.790 --> 00:50:43.160
Everyone still has
thousands of chips.

00:50:43.160 --> 00:50:46.400
There are cases where you could
construct an extreme case where

00:50:46.400 --> 00:50:48.510
you should fold aces
preflop in a tournament,

00:50:48.510 --> 00:50:51.601
in a normal tournament as well.

00:50:51.601 --> 00:50:56.260
OK, so let's get back
to the tournament now.

00:50:56.260 --> 00:50:57.500
OK, where were we?

00:50:57.500 --> 00:51:01.730
So we lost a bunch
of chips here.

00:51:01.730 --> 00:51:05.205
So the next hand we
get king-8 offsuit.

00:51:05.205 --> 00:51:07.880
I raise from the button.

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:09.390
So we are committed here.

00:51:09.390 --> 00:51:12.410
It sucks because our hand
sucks, but it's way too

00:51:12.410 --> 00:51:14.180
good odds to call.

00:51:14.180 --> 00:51:16.060
And ICM is nowhere
near that relevant

00:51:16.060 --> 00:51:17.870
when it's against
the small stack.

00:51:17.870 --> 00:51:19.710
It's the guy you're
trying to eliminate.

00:51:19.710 --> 00:51:20.210
So we call.

00:51:20.210 --> 00:51:23.540
We get pretty lucky here.

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:27.140
Good redemption for that
terrible jack-10 hand

00:51:27.140 --> 00:51:27.830
played by me.

00:51:27.830 --> 00:51:30.320
OK, so there's
three players left.

00:51:30.320 --> 00:51:32.300
So ICM is still very relevant.

00:51:32.300 --> 00:51:33.820
We're the second stack.

00:51:33.820 --> 00:51:38.420
So we're trying not to get in
a big all-in with this guy,

00:51:38.420 --> 00:51:42.020
although it's less significant
because this guy still

00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:43.400
has a decent amount of chips.

00:51:43.400 --> 00:51:45.290
If this guy only
had 50,000 chips,

00:51:45.290 --> 00:51:47.930
then I would try a lot
harder to avoid getting

00:51:47.930 --> 00:51:51.080
in a big pot with BeMySponsor.

00:51:51.080 --> 00:51:52.260
So-- oops.

00:51:52.260 --> 00:51:56.100
So yeah, so he raises,
and LPMBox goes all in,

00:51:56.100 --> 00:51:56.960
takes it down.

00:52:00.380 --> 00:52:03.230
So this hand, he makes it 3x.

00:52:03.230 --> 00:52:07.250
And I decide to call it here
with queen-6 suited, which

00:52:07.250 --> 00:52:08.450
is gutsy I think.

00:52:08.450 --> 00:52:11.810
But I think it's in position,
and it's fairly deep.

00:52:11.810 --> 00:52:14.967
And being able to put ICM
pressure on him is reasonable.

00:52:14.967 --> 00:52:16.550
I think it could
have gone either way.

00:52:18.969 --> 00:52:20.510
Folding is definitely
the safer play,

00:52:20.510 --> 00:52:24.890
but queen-6 suited is
plenty good enough here.

00:52:24.890 --> 00:52:25.910
So I call.

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:27.334
He just checks.

00:52:27.334 --> 00:52:29.000
He might just be
giving up on this board

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:32.150
where there's a decent amount
of-- it's fairly dry, right?

00:52:32.150 --> 00:52:35.245
So from what I said last class,
if the board is fairly dry,

00:52:35.245 --> 00:52:38.360
where every hand has something,
if you've got absolutely

00:52:38.360 --> 00:52:40.310
nothing, then
there's not even much

00:52:40.310 --> 00:52:43.910
point to make a bluff like if
he's got ace-2 offsuit here.

00:52:43.910 --> 00:52:47.030
So he just checks in,
and I bet, and he folds.

00:52:47.030 --> 00:52:51.710
So he probably had ace-2
offsuit some hand like that.

00:52:51.710 --> 00:52:53.800
Next hand we get ace-king.

00:52:53.800 --> 00:52:56.090
I decide to raise
small here once again.

00:52:56.090 --> 00:53:00.680
So I guess this protects
that jack-10 hand.

00:53:00.680 --> 00:53:02.180
If I'm doing this
with jack-10, I

00:53:02.180 --> 00:53:04.970
do need to do it with good
hands as well to protect

00:53:04.970 --> 00:53:07.520
the times I do have jack-10.

00:53:07.520 --> 00:53:09.630
Unfortunately, he
guesses correctly.

00:53:09.630 --> 00:53:11.560
He doesn't fold, and I
have jack-10 and folds.

00:53:11.560 --> 00:53:12.393
And I have ace-king.

00:53:14.590 --> 00:53:16.400
So he still take that one downs.

00:53:16.400 --> 00:53:18.890
And we win the blinds
the next hand again.

00:53:18.890 --> 00:53:22.730
So suddenly we're worried
chip leader by a decent margin

00:53:22.730 --> 00:53:25.430
after those three hands.

00:53:25.430 --> 00:53:30.730
9-4 off-- I'm not going
to call, so fold to him.

00:53:30.730 --> 00:53:33.060
So jack-7, so once
again, because of ICM,

00:53:33.060 --> 00:53:35.690
this guy just goes all in
knowing we can't call that

00:53:35.690 --> 00:53:36.670
much.

00:53:36.670 --> 00:53:39.210
Takes it down.

00:53:39.210 --> 00:53:41.570
7-6 offsuit, I decide to fold.

00:53:41.570 --> 00:53:44.450
I think that's very reasonable
considering they can just

00:53:44.450 --> 00:53:45.650
go all in on top of that.

00:53:48.920 --> 00:53:50.830
Queen-9, queen-9
off, get a walk.

00:53:50.830 --> 00:53:52.330
So one thing I
should pay attention

00:53:52.330 --> 00:53:54.340
is I do think these guys--

00:53:54.340 --> 00:53:56.680
by now I've collected
enough data points

00:53:56.680 --> 00:53:59.180
of getting a walk way
more often than I should,

00:53:59.180 --> 00:54:01.790
where I think it's not
just a coincidence.

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:05.200
I'm statistically confident
enough that they're actually

00:54:05.200 --> 00:54:06.610
just giving me too many walks.

00:54:06.610 --> 00:54:09.120
So when they don't
give me a walk,

00:54:09.120 --> 00:54:11.470
I should put them on a
stronger range of hands

00:54:11.470 --> 00:54:14.080
than I normally do.

00:54:14.080 --> 00:54:16.080
Pocket 10s, we three-bet
this guy again.

00:54:16.080 --> 00:54:17.110
He gets away again.

00:54:19.950 --> 00:54:22.317
So 6-2 off, so we've
gotten dealt good cards

00:54:22.317 --> 00:54:24.650
even though we haven't gotten
too much action from them.

00:54:24.650 --> 00:54:28.000
We're still winning by two
chips from getting good cards.

00:54:31.120 --> 00:54:33.120
So jack-4 off, I'm going
to fold to this guy.

00:54:33.120 --> 00:54:34.930
So as you can see,
it's fairly boring,

00:54:34.930 --> 00:54:38.860
but I think this
is what essentially

00:54:38.860 --> 00:54:43.000
should happen in the
final couple of people

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:44.280
left in the tournament.

00:54:44.280 --> 00:54:50.860
Ace-10 off, so I decide
to not go all in here.

00:54:50.860 --> 00:54:52.915
I guess that would be 27 big--

00:54:52.915 --> 00:54:56.420
26 and a 1/2 big blinds,
which is a bit much.

00:54:56.420 --> 00:54:59.650
So I decided to
just raise small.

00:54:59.650 --> 00:55:03.460
If he three-bets, if he
reraises to, say, 60,000,

00:55:03.460 --> 00:55:05.680
I'm always going all in here.

00:55:05.680 --> 00:55:10.540
If he goes all in himself,
I'm basically not folding

00:55:10.540 --> 00:55:13.417
even though it sucks from
an ICM point of view.

00:55:13.417 --> 00:55:15.250
I think ace-10 offsuit
is just way too good.

00:55:15.250 --> 00:55:19.330
So I'm essentially just raising
small looking for action here.

00:55:19.330 --> 00:55:19.960
He folds.

00:55:23.440 --> 00:55:25.540
7-2 offsuit, we raise-- no.

00:55:25.540 --> 00:55:27.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:27.050 --> 00:55:31.820
So LPMBox gets a walk.

00:55:31.820 --> 00:55:34.620
Queen-3 off, we get another
walk, which is nice.

00:55:38.580 --> 00:55:42.630
Jack-5 off, I raise
here, which is definitely

00:55:42.630 --> 00:55:43.930
an exploitative play.

00:55:43.930 --> 00:55:47.950
It's definitely not-- definitely
from a Nash equilibrium optimal

00:55:47.950 --> 00:55:50.890
play point of view,
there's no way

00:55:50.890 --> 00:55:53.780
the optimal strategy is to
raise a fraction of hand

00:55:53.780 --> 00:55:56.320
so big that it includes
jack-5 offsuit.

00:55:56.320 --> 00:55:59.200
But I think at the
time, I probably

00:55:59.200 --> 00:56:01.985
told myself, this guy
was being overly scared.

00:56:01.985 --> 00:56:04.450
Even though he was playing
somewhat aggressive earlier on,

00:56:04.450 --> 00:56:07.870
he is maybe
overadjusting for ICM

00:56:07.870 --> 00:56:10.420
and is respecting me
too much in the presence

00:56:10.420 --> 00:56:12.610
of this short stack.

00:56:12.610 --> 00:56:14.800
I can look at the HUD
stats at the time,

00:56:14.800 --> 00:56:18.580
although they won't be that
accurate because they're

00:56:18.580 --> 00:56:20.920
going to include all the hands.

00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:24.460
So normally I do play
with all these numbers on.

00:56:24.460 --> 00:56:26.270
So we can see that his--

00:56:26.270 --> 00:56:28.090
yeah, but it's
going to be biased

00:56:28.090 --> 00:56:31.870
because this includes
the hands with six

00:56:31.870 --> 00:56:33.490
or seven people at the table.

00:56:33.490 --> 00:56:38.860
But it says that he calls
from the big blind only 20%

00:56:38.860 --> 00:56:39.370
of the time.

00:56:39.370 --> 00:56:41.882
But that's not a great--

00:56:41.882 --> 00:56:43.090
yeah, that's going to biased.

00:56:43.090 --> 00:56:46.870
So it doesn't tell us too much.

00:56:46.870 --> 00:56:48.929
But I guess at the time,
I must have told myself

00:56:48.929 --> 00:56:50.470
I'm going to try to
exploit this guy.

00:56:50.470 --> 00:56:53.080
That's the only way I
can see why I decided

00:56:53.080 --> 00:56:55.810
to raise jack-5 offsuit here.

00:56:55.810 --> 00:56:56.740
So we get a call.

00:56:56.740 --> 00:56:59.170
But I'm going to
continuation bet.

00:56:59.170 --> 00:57:01.300
We do have a
backdoor heart draw,

00:57:01.300 --> 00:57:04.300
and this is our best chance
of just winning the pot.

00:57:04.300 --> 00:57:06.970
And I could maybe barrel on--

00:57:06.970 --> 00:57:10.790
by barrel, I mean bet again as
a bluff on a bunch of turns.

00:57:10.790 --> 00:57:13.110
So I just bet here.

00:57:13.110 --> 00:57:13.780
He does fold.

00:57:17.950 --> 00:57:19.870
Next hand with queen-9,
we open the button,

00:57:19.870 --> 00:57:21.760
but we get shoved on.

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:23.440
And I guess we have to fold.

00:57:27.670 --> 00:57:29.010
Queen-4, we get another walk.

00:57:29.010 --> 00:57:30.843
Yes, so this is actually
getting ridiculous.

00:57:30.843 --> 00:57:32.950
It seems like we've
literally gotten

00:57:32.950 --> 00:57:34.510
five or six walks in a row.

00:57:34.510 --> 00:57:40.000
And I would guess probably we
should be getting a walk less--

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:42.940
I guess at a three-handed
table, it's more often but still

00:57:42.940 --> 00:57:45.282
less than like 30% of the time.

00:57:45.282 --> 00:57:45.781
Yeah?

00:57:45.781 --> 00:57:47.406
AUDIENCE: Is it
possible you're getting

00:57:47.406 --> 00:57:51.030
walks because someone
has raised your big blind

00:57:51.030 --> 00:57:52.640
and you defended a lot?

00:57:52.640 --> 00:57:55.005
And so they're scared
to raise your big blind?

00:57:55.005 --> 00:57:55.630
WILL MA: Maybe.

00:57:55.630 --> 00:57:57.520
I have been fairly active.

00:57:57.520 --> 00:57:58.960
But I did fold a bunch of--

00:57:58.960 --> 00:58:02.350
I did fold some borderline
situations, though,

00:58:02.350 --> 00:58:03.424
like this jack--

00:58:03.424 --> 00:58:04.840
I think it was a
different jack-7.

00:58:04.840 --> 00:58:06.814
But yeah, maybe.

00:58:06.814 --> 00:58:07.480
That's possibly.

00:58:07.480 --> 00:58:09.826
Yeah, very good point.

00:58:09.826 --> 00:58:10.805
But that's good, right?

00:58:10.805 --> 00:58:11.930
It's good that we're like--

00:58:11.930 --> 00:58:16.640
I'm not complaining that
we're getting a lot of stuff.

00:58:16.640 --> 00:58:20.470
And we are the big stack, so in
general, it is harder for them

00:58:20.470 --> 00:58:22.810
to bully us around than
us to bully them around.

00:58:22.810 --> 00:58:25.870
So it does make sense from
that point of view, too.

00:58:25.870 --> 00:58:27.905
I saw that it was just too many.

00:58:27.905 --> 00:58:29.280
Anyway, so I just
continue trying

00:58:29.280 --> 00:58:32.230
to raise a lot, especially
against this guy.

00:58:32.230 --> 00:58:35.420
So jack-8 offsuit,
we take it down.

00:58:35.420 --> 00:58:37.420
Jack-2, maybe we
could have folded.

00:58:37.420 --> 00:58:39.940
But by now this guy was
getting short enough.

00:58:39.940 --> 00:58:42.760
He's blinded down from
15 and 1/2 big blinds,

00:58:42.760 --> 00:58:44.530
I think, to 13 and 1/2.

00:58:44.530 --> 00:58:46.570
He might have had
more before, like 17.

00:58:46.570 --> 00:58:50.260
So he might be looking
for a spot to shove now.

00:58:50.260 --> 00:58:52.170
BeMySponsor actually
raises a small here

00:58:52.170 --> 00:58:53.710
and gets him to fold.

00:58:57.895 --> 00:59:00.200
And jack-6 off here.

00:59:00.200 --> 00:59:01.040
We get another walk.

00:59:01.040 --> 00:59:02.790
I should just skip the
hands on big blinds

00:59:02.790 --> 00:59:07.660
since nothing ever happens,
which is great for us.

00:59:07.660 --> 00:59:10.810
So pocket 3s here,
I just go all in.

00:59:10.810 --> 00:59:14.700
So I talked about this before.

00:59:14.700 --> 00:59:17.470
What's a problem with what
this play in some sense?

00:59:21.350 --> 00:59:23.800
AUDIENCE: Reverse implied odds?

00:59:23.800 --> 00:59:24.860
WILL MA: Right, good.

00:59:24.860 --> 00:59:27.900
So yeah, so if I don't do
this, if I just raise small,

00:59:27.900 --> 00:59:30.890
I have bad reverse
implied odds, right?

00:59:30.890 --> 00:59:34.140
But one particular issue
is every other time

00:59:34.140 --> 00:59:35.910
we've made it 25,000.

00:59:35.910 --> 00:59:38.820
And really nothing's changed,
and suddenly we go all in.

00:59:38.820 --> 00:59:42.800
So it is a bit suspicious
where he basically

00:59:42.800 --> 00:59:46.440
knows we have a hand that has
very bad reverse implied odds.

00:59:46.440 --> 00:59:49.680
He basically knows we have
pocket 3s or ace-4 offsuit

00:59:49.680 --> 00:59:50.640
or something like that.

00:59:50.640 --> 00:59:54.240
But it's still hard
for him to exploit.

00:59:54.240 --> 00:59:57.570
I mean sure, you can call
ace-9 and exploit us,

00:59:57.570 --> 01:00:00.090
but ace-9 is already
a great hand.

01:00:00.090 --> 01:00:02.370
Or you can call pocket
4s and exploit us,

01:00:02.370 --> 01:00:06.000
but it's not that easy to get
dealt pocket 4s or a better

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:07.970
pair than pocket 4s.

01:00:07.970 --> 01:00:13.160
So here yeah, even though
against a good player, he knows

01:00:13.160 --> 01:00:15.990
my range is a very small
specific number of hands.

01:00:15.990 --> 01:00:17.630
It's still hard for him to--

01:00:17.630 --> 01:00:20.080
he can't really just
call jack-10 suited here.

01:00:20.080 --> 01:00:24.200
Maybe he can, but probably
jack-9 suited or queen-7

01:00:24.200 --> 01:00:27.810
suited he can't call
because there's still

01:00:27.810 --> 01:00:31.491
an off chance we have
queen-9 offsuit or something.

01:00:31.491 --> 01:00:32.750
Oops.

01:00:32.750 --> 01:00:35.280
So anyway, so he does fold.

01:00:35.280 --> 01:00:38.180
But it definitely
raises suspicion.

01:00:38.180 --> 01:00:42.415
Jack-10 off, so jack-10
off, we just go all in here.

01:00:42.415 --> 01:00:44.410
So this is actually important.

01:00:44.410 --> 01:00:46.770
So normally I would just
raise from the button,

01:00:46.770 --> 01:00:49.020
but by now, the big
blind has gotten

01:00:49.020 --> 01:00:51.870
so short that I'm
willing to just go

01:00:51.870 --> 01:00:55.350
all in because the big blind is
short enough where even if he

01:00:55.350 --> 01:00:57.450
picks up a hand and
calls and beats me,

01:00:57.450 --> 01:00:59.890
I'm still the chip leader,
even if that happens.

01:00:59.890 --> 01:01:03.880
So the ICM doesn't hurt
me that much because--

01:01:03.880 --> 01:01:07.860
yeah, and also just the
fact that I'm risking less.

01:01:07.860 --> 01:01:10.500
The other important thing of
the big blind getting short

01:01:10.500 --> 01:01:14.160
is now the small blind is much
less incentivized to gamble

01:01:14.160 --> 01:01:15.240
than before.

01:01:15.240 --> 01:01:18.840
Before, when the
big blind had 180K,

01:01:18.840 --> 01:01:21.120
he was incentivizing
gambling against me

01:01:21.120 --> 01:01:25.530
because it's not that easy to
wait for the big blind to bust.

01:01:25.530 --> 01:01:27.870
But now that the big
blind only has 10K,

01:01:27.870 --> 01:01:30.630
it's easier to just wait
and hope that he busts.

01:01:30.630 --> 01:01:34.710
So basically ICM becomes a lot
more favorable in both cases.

01:01:34.710 --> 01:01:39.060
And shoving, I think, is very
good now with the stack sizes.

01:01:39.060 --> 01:01:42.600
So we do shove, and
we take it down.

01:01:42.600 --> 01:01:45.690
9-2 off, so no one
usually wants our blinds,

01:01:45.690 --> 01:01:48.410
but then they both
want our blinds.

01:01:48.410 --> 01:01:49.760
LPMBox takes it down.

01:01:53.480 --> 01:01:56.240
So ace-2, I just go all in here.

01:01:56.240 --> 01:02:00.120
Basically same justification
as the pocket 3s.

01:02:00.120 --> 01:02:05.210
8-7 off, I think I probably
should have raised this.

01:02:05.210 --> 01:02:08.480
Even going all in honestly
might not be that bad.

01:02:08.480 --> 01:02:09.980
I'd have to do an
exact calculation,

01:02:09.980 --> 01:02:12.140
but I think probably--

01:02:12.140 --> 01:02:13.130
it's a pretty bad hand.

01:02:13.130 --> 01:02:16.010
But I think probably I
shouldn't be folding given

01:02:16.010 --> 01:02:18.440
that I'm the big stack and
given that they've both

01:02:18.440 --> 01:02:20.240
been giving me lots of respect.

01:02:20.240 --> 01:02:22.950
But I fold, which
can be a big mistake.

01:02:22.950 --> 01:02:26.500
But I think probably I
shouldn't have folded.

01:02:26.500 --> 01:02:29.370
The next hand, LPMBox
goes all in, and we fold.

01:02:34.280 --> 01:02:37.150
Next hand, we 8-7
suited, so by now,

01:02:37.150 --> 01:02:40.080
this guy, BeMySponsor,
so we've just won enough

01:02:40.080 --> 01:02:42.610
pots where this guy
is also short now.

01:02:42.610 --> 01:02:45.590
So it's a pretty good situation
for us from an ICM perspective.

01:02:45.590 --> 01:02:48.910
They're both short enough where
we can just go all in preflop

01:02:48.910 --> 01:02:53.110
very often and they have
to fold quite often.

01:02:53.110 --> 01:02:55.780
10-7 off is a bit too weak,
but I decide to raise.

01:02:55.780 --> 01:02:58.030
But yeah, this is a bit
inconsistent play from my part

01:02:58.030 --> 01:03:00.480
because I think
for most purposes,

01:03:00.480 --> 01:03:03.470
8-7 off is a better
hand than 10-7 off.

01:03:03.470 --> 01:03:09.070
But for some reason I raise
10-7 off and fold 8-7 off.

01:03:09.070 --> 01:03:10.960
He's 5-suited.

01:03:10.960 --> 01:03:13.150
We get a walk again.

01:03:13.150 --> 01:03:16.780
Queen-5 off, yeah, so
I just go all in here.

01:03:16.780 --> 01:03:19.930
So this is definitely not
a plus chip EV all-in,

01:03:19.930 --> 01:03:22.450
but once again I
think ICM by now

01:03:22.450 --> 01:03:26.500
is relevant enough where
it's fine because he just

01:03:26.500 --> 01:03:31.070
has to fold, weakening it down.

01:03:31.070 --> 01:03:33.610
10-6 off, I decide to fold.

01:03:33.610 --> 01:03:35.950
Big blind gets a walk.

01:03:35.950 --> 01:03:39.380
Get a walk with
6-deuce pretty good.

01:03:39.380 --> 01:03:41.070
Ace-2 off, once
again, we go all in.

01:03:41.070 --> 01:03:42.560
They fold.

01:03:42.560 --> 01:03:44.300
Pocket kings, so I basically--

01:03:44.300 --> 01:03:44.929
AUDIENCE: Wow.

01:03:44.929 --> 01:03:46.970
WILL MA: Yeah, so this is
a bit suspicious again.

01:03:46.970 --> 01:03:48.850
Normally I've been going all in.

01:03:48.850 --> 01:03:49.530
He raises small.

01:03:49.530 --> 01:03:52.670
Obviously yes, pocket kings.

01:03:52.670 --> 01:03:54.740
So yeah, that's basically true.

01:03:54.740 --> 01:03:56.630
But I mean also I
think I will do this

01:03:56.630 --> 01:03:58.880
with some of the
weakest hands that I'm

01:03:58.880 --> 01:04:00.800
not willing to
gamble all in with

01:04:00.800 --> 01:04:05.600
but still want to raise maybe
something like 9-7 offsuit

01:04:05.600 --> 01:04:07.220
maybe.

01:04:07.220 --> 01:04:12.170
But we don't play it,
so we take it down.

01:04:12.170 --> 01:04:13.040
So he goes all in.

01:04:13.040 --> 01:04:14.110
We fold jack-2 offsuit.

01:04:17.340 --> 01:04:18.627
Queen-3 suited, go all in.

01:04:18.627 --> 01:04:20.460
So I'm going to go
through this fairly fast.

01:04:20.460 --> 01:04:22.310
There's a lot of same stuff.

01:04:22.310 --> 01:04:26.895
6-5 off, we fold because
yeah, by now they're

01:04:26.895 --> 01:04:29.020
short enough where they
might actually just call us

01:04:29.020 --> 01:04:30.310
pretty often.

01:04:30.310 --> 01:04:32.830
So I fold 6-5 off.

01:04:32.830 --> 01:04:36.430
So here, pocket 3s holds
against queen-jack.

01:04:36.430 --> 01:04:39.250
So this is an extreme ICM spot.

01:04:39.250 --> 01:04:42.010
So he calls here, and
he does double up.

01:04:42.010 --> 01:04:46.120
So the next hand, we do
have an extreme ICM spot

01:04:46.120 --> 01:04:48.970
because this guy only
has one big blind.

01:04:48.970 --> 01:04:50.770
So essentially their
correct strategy

01:04:50.770 --> 01:04:53.290
is going to be I'm supposed
to shove any two cards.

01:04:53.290 --> 01:04:56.590
And he's only supposed
to call, I would guess,

01:04:56.590 --> 01:05:02.080
maybe the top 7% or 8%
of hands in a situation.

01:05:02.080 --> 01:05:05.410
He normally should be
calling top 30 or something.

01:05:05.410 --> 01:05:07.380
So I just go all in.

01:05:07.380 --> 01:05:11.660
Even if he has ace-2 offsuit,
I'm certain he has to fold.

01:05:11.660 --> 01:05:15.520
Even if he has, say, king-queen,
and I turn up my hand

01:05:15.520 --> 01:05:17.335
and show him jack-8,
he probably still

01:05:17.335 --> 01:05:23.275
has to fold just because
he really can't bust.

01:05:23.275 --> 01:05:25.570
I haven't done the
exact math, but I

01:05:25.570 --> 01:05:27.520
wouldn't be that
surprised if he told me

01:05:27.520 --> 01:05:29.140
pocket 9s is a fold for him.

01:05:29.140 --> 01:05:32.100
I wouldn't be that
surprised, so yeah.

01:05:36.070 --> 01:05:39.160
So once again, I go all in
because this guy probably

01:05:39.160 --> 01:05:39.850
can't call.

01:05:44.900 --> 01:05:46.440
Oh, OK, so yeah.

01:05:46.440 --> 01:05:48.927
We win against
ace-queen, which is crazy

01:05:48.927 --> 01:05:51.260
that they picked up ace-queen
with one big blind, right?

01:05:51.260 --> 01:05:51.760
Anyway.

01:05:51.760 --> 01:05:52.530
[LAUGHTER]

01:05:53.130 --> 01:05:57.720
Some players like to do this
thing called cooperative play

01:05:57.720 --> 01:06:01.350
to get that big blind to bust.

01:06:01.350 --> 01:06:04.470
In the history of
poker, it's what

01:06:04.470 --> 01:06:09.620
was almost customary for the
players who have chips in here

01:06:09.620 --> 01:06:12.660
to basically just all agree
to just call and not raise

01:06:12.660 --> 01:06:16.140
each other and to maximize
their chances of busting

01:06:16.140 --> 01:06:17.117
the big blind.

01:06:17.117 --> 01:06:18.700
It's a form of
cheating in some sense.

01:06:18.700 --> 01:06:20.320
It's collusion in some sense.

01:06:20.320 --> 01:06:23.930
But it's customary maybe
five-six years ago for everyone

01:06:23.930 --> 01:06:28.140
to do this because it
benefits everyone else.

01:06:28.140 --> 01:06:33.150
It benefits all of these guys
if they all agree to do this.

01:06:33.150 --> 01:06:35.760
And it just
maximizes the chances

01:06:35.760 --> 01:06:37.650
that the big blind
is eliminated.

01:06:37.650 --> 01:06:43.950
But the issue with
this is unfortunately

01:06:43.950 --> 01:06:46.170
there is an option
to be selfish.

01:06:46.170 --> 01:06:50.640
Unfortunately, if we both
trusted each other completely,

01:06:50.640 --> 01:06:53.760
we could collude and be like,
OK, we're just going to call,

01:06:53.760 --> 01:06:56.250
check down every flop
turn and river no matter

01:06:56.250 --> 01:06:59.160
what to match so that we can
both see the river with any two

01:06:59.160 --> 01:07:02.010
cards and maximize the
chances of busting this guy.

01:07:02.010 --> 01:07:09.180
The issue with this is when you
play a game, you're selfish.

01:07:09.180 --> 01:07:10.950
If there is an
opportunity to bet

01:07:10.950 --> 01:07:14.469
because you have a good hand,
you're going to want to bet.

01:07:14.469 --> 01:07:16.260
If there's a draw and
you have a good hand,

01:07:16.260 --> 01:07:18.210
you want to bet to get
the other guy to fold.

01:07:18.210 --> 01:07:21.420
And basically from a game
theoretic perspective,

01:07:21.420 --> 01:07:23.250
since we have these
options, there's

01:07:23.250 --> 01:07:25.650
no way for us to
essentially agree

01:07:25.650 --> 01:07:28.320
that we're going to just check
down and see the river, which

01:07:28.320 --> 01:07:32.630
is why I consider collusion
of players actually do this.

01:07:32.630 --> 01:07:35.760
So nonetheless, I do
the most selfish line,

01:07:35.760 --> 01:07:37.680
which is just go all in.

01:07:37.680 --> 01:07:40.050
But yeah, if this guy
was my best friend

01:07:40.050 --> 01:07:43.350
and I wanted to cheat, then
I could just call and let

01:07:43.350 --> 01:07:45.300
him call and then
just check it down

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:46.680
even if I flopped the nut flush.

01:07:51.850 --> 01:07:54.630
OK, so now it's heads up.

01:07:54.630 --> 01:07:57.780
OK, I'll try to show every hand.

01:07:57.780 --> 01:07:59.105
OK, so now ICM doesn't matter.

01:07:59.105 --> 01:08:01.230
But it would be good to
show a little heads up play

01:08:01.230 --> 01:08:03.780
because I don't think
we've done too much

01:08:03.780 --> 01:08:05.910
heads up play in this class.

01:08:05.910 --> 01:08:07.230
So we call here.

01:08:07.230 --> 01:08:09.990
And we check.

01:08:09.990 --> 01:08:11.520
He makes it 32.

01:08:11.520 --> 01:08:16.359
And I just have to
check-raise bluff this flop.

01:08:16.359 --> 01:08:17.460
I think it's close.

01:08:17.460 --> 01:08:20.370
I think I probably
shouldn't be folding.

01:08:20.370 --> 01:08:23.370
I think jack-6 suited
just has too many backdoor

01:08:23.370 --> 01:08:28.529
draws on this flop to ever fold
just as part of my strategy.

01:08:28.529 --> 01:08:31.720
I think I decided that I
wanted my strategy to be I'm

01:08:31.720 --> 01:08:35.490
going to raise good
hands, like 8s and 4s.

01:08:35.490 --> 01:08:38.520
And then I'm going to also raise
hands with lots of backdoor

01:08:38.520 --> 01:08:40.290
draws like jack-6 of hearts.

01:08:40.290 --> 01:08:43.950
So I decide to do this.

01:08:43.950 --> 01:08:47.890
So unfortunately he
goes all in, so we fold.

01:08:47.890 --> 01:08:48.890
It doesn't quite work.

01:08:51.740 --> 01:08:55.054
So queen-10 off, we raise.

01:08:55.054 --> 01:08:56.470
Oh, so one thing
I should say is--

01:08:56.470 --> 01:08:59.140
I think most of you know
this-- but once a tournament

01:08:59.140 --> 01:09:02.319
gets heads up and it's just a
small blind and the big blind,

01:09:02.319 --> 01:09:04.514
the small blind is
actually has position.

01:09:04.514 --> 01:09:06.680
So normally when it's small
blind against big blind,

01:09:06.680 --> 01:09:08.790
the bid blind has
position postflop.

01:09:08.790 --> 01:09:10.810
But when it's heads
up as a small blind,

01:09:10.810 --> 01:09:12.160
you actually have position.

01:09:12.160 --> 01:09:14.483
So you're very strongly
incentivized to play

01:09:14.483 --> 01:09:15.399
from this small blind.

01:09:15.399 --> 01:09:17.380
It's just by far
the better position

01:09:17.380 --> 01:09:20.150
because you have
position, and you

01:09:20.150 --> 01:09:22.810
have to put in less of a blind.

01:09:22.810 --> 01:09:25.029
So another cheat that--
so I'm teaching you guys

01:09:25.029 --> 01:09:26.356
all these different cheats.

01:09:26.356 --> 01:09:27.939
Another cheat that
people used to do--

01:09:27.939 --> 01:09:28.990
it's not really a cheat.

01:09:28.990 --> 01:09:33.460
But another angle shoot people
used to do back in the day is

01:09:33.460 --> 01:09:36.970
there would be people who
normally play pretty low

01:09:36.970 --> 01:09:41.109
stakes, let's say, $0.25, $0.50.

01:09:41.109 --> 01:09:44.260
They would set up
these $25, $50 tables.

01:09:44.260 --> 01:09:47.020
So where the blinds
are $25, $50, which

01:09:47.020 --> 01:09:50.500
is really high stakes for them.

01:09:50.500 --> 01:09:53.200
They really don't have the
bankroll to gamble that.

01:09:53.200 --> 01:09:55.180
But their strategy
basically is if you're

01:09:55.180 --> 01:09:57.910
the first to sit
down, you get to be

01:09:57.910 --> 01:09:59.590
the dealer on the first hand.

01:09:59.590 --> 01:10:02.440
So their strategy
is basically just

01:10:02.440 --> 01:10:05.019
sit there and then wait for
someone else to sit down.

01:10:05.019 --> 01:10:07.060
And then play the first
hand as the dealer, where

01:10:07.060 --> 01:10:08.810
they have a huge advantage.

01:10:08.810 --> 01:10:11.185
They can just raise, and
usually the other guy will fold,

01:10:11.185 --> 01:10:14.320
and they'll win 50 bucks,
which is a huge deal to them.

01:10:14.320 --> 01:10:16.900
And then they'll just
leave after the first hand.

01:10:16.900 --> 01:10:19.840
So this is something that
happened quite a lot.

01:10:19.840 --> 01:10:21.520
So my friends and
I, we've talked

01:10:21.520 --> 01:10:23.740
about playing a
crazy strategy, where

01:10:23.740 --> 01:10:26.400
you would sit down knowing this
is what the other guy's going

01:10:26.400 --> 01:10:27.130
to do.

01:10:27.130 --> 01:10:28.960
And then sit down with him.

01:10:28.960 --> 01:10:31.240
We would have the
capital to take on risk.

01:10:31.240 --> 01:10:33.550
And then we would basically
just play the first hand

01:10:33.550 --> 01:10:35.340
extremely aggressively.

01:10:35.340 --> 01:10:37.900
And knowing that the guy has
been fold most of the time,

01:10:37.900 --> 01:10:41.570
because if he calls, that's
all his money on the site.

01:10:41.570 --> 01:10:45.154
So yeah, it led to a
lot of weird dynamics.

01:10:45.154 --> 01:10:47.840
But OK, so here we have--

01:10:47.840 --> 01:10:50.410
This is why I chose
tournaments, not cash games.

01:10:50.410 --> 01:10:52.720
There's fewer ways to do
these when you use cheats.

01:10:52.720 --> 01:10:54.535
So queen-10, we raise.

01:10:54.535 --> 01:10:57.228
We take it down.

01:10:57.228 --> 01:10:59.110
Next hand we get
ace-queen suited.

01:10:59.110 --> 01:11:00.590
So unfortunately we get a walk.

01:11:03.190 --> 01:11:05.260
So queen-8, we raise.

01:11:05.260 --> 01:11:08.080
We take it down--
sorry, he calls.

01:11:08.080 --> 01:11:09.340
And then it's checked to us.

01:11:09.340 --> 01:11:11.380
We continuation bet.

01:11:11.380 --> 01:11:14.890
And he raises, which
is weird because it's

01:11:14.890 --> 01:11:17.521
a flop that's a lot better
for my range than his

01:11:17.521 --> 01:11:19.270
because I can have
ace-king and ace-queen.

01:11:19.270 --> 01:11:21.228
And even ace-jack, I
think, if he had ace-jack,

01:11:21.228 --> 01:11:23.260
he would have reraised preflop.

01:11:23.260 --> 01:11:27.389
So in some sense it's
weird because it's

01:11:27.389 --> 01:11:28.930
really hard for him
to have, I think,

01:11:28.930 --> 01:11:30.640
pocket aces or pocket 8s.

01:11:30.640 --> 01:11:32.910
Or even pocket 3s,
he probably would

01:11:32.910 --> 01:11:34.330
have reraised all on preflop.

01:11:34.330 --> 01:11:36.662
So really it's like,
what do you have?

01:11:36.662 --> 01:11:37.870
It's like, I don't have much.

01:11:37.870 --> 01:11:40.540
But really it's like,
what do you have?

01:11:40.540 --> 01:11:45.970
So it's weird because I expect
him to check-raise this flop so

01:11:45.970 --> 01:11:49.740
rarely that what he does, on
the one hand, it's just strange.

01:11:49.740 --> 01:11:52.570
But on the other hand,
he must know that.

01:11:52.570 --> 01:11:54.160
I'm assuming it's
somewhat balanced,

01:11:54.160 --> 01:11:57.670
and he will occasionally turn
up ace-3 or something here.

01:11:57.670 --> 01:12:00.760
So I decide to call
and see one more card.

01:12:00.760 --> 01:12:02.890
I don't know if that's great.

01:12:02.890 --> 01:12:05.350
Maybe I should have just
folded and just believed him

01:12:05.350 --> 01:12:08.770
or just reraised if
I didn't believe him.

01:12:08.770 --> 01:12:10.210
Reraise essentially is a bluff.

01:12:10.210 --> 01:12:13.540
Make it 100,000, and
just hope he folds.

01:12:13.540 --> 01:12:14.800
But I decide to call.

01:12:14.800 --> 01:12:17.380
The turn is a 9 putting
out some straight draws

01:12:17.380 --> 01:12:19.330
but no flush draws.

01:12:19.330 --> 01:12:22.420
That's fairly big, and I fold.

01:12:22.420 --> 01:12:25.090
I don't really know how I feel
about how I played that hand.

01:12:25.090 --> 01:12:27.400
I think I mostly
played exploitatively.

01:12:27.400 --> 01:12:30.120
I just called the flop because
I wanted to see what he did,

01:12:30.120 --> 01:12:32.400
and I folded the
turn because maybe

01:12:32.400 --> 01:12:35.020
based on his bet sizing
or his bet timing,

01:12:35.020 --> 01:12:36.150
I just felt like he had it.

01:12:36.150 --> 01:12:39.029
So I'm not sure I'm
extremely happy with how

01:12:39.029 --> 01:12:39.820
I played that hand.

01:12:39.820 --> 01:12:41.950
But probably just at
the time, I decided

01:12:41.950 --> 01:12:45.310
to play exploitatively and
try to play best against how

01:12:45.310 --> 01:12:47.680
I expect him to act.

01:12:47.680 --> 01:12:54.160
So here 10-7 off, I
decide to reraise.

01:12:54.160 --> 01:12:57.720
So the reason I reraise a
hand as bad as 10-7 offsuit--

01:12:57.720 --> 01:13:01.360
I talked a bit about this two
classes ago about your preflop

01:13:01.360 --> 01:13:02.560
raising strategy.

01:13:02.560 --> 01:13:04.360
So essentially
what I'm doing is I

01:13:04.360 --> 01:13:06.820
want to be reraising
my good hands

01:13:06.820 --> 01:13:10.690
and also my hands that I'm
not sad if he goes all in,

01:13:10.690 --> 01:13:13.060
and I have to fold, and I
don't get to see a flop with.

01:13:13.060 --> 01:13:17.420
So if I had 10-7 suited,
that's too good of a hand.

01:13:17.420 --> 01:13:19.300
And I really don't
want to reraise.

01:13:19.300 --> 01:13:22.480
And then if he goes all in,
fold my pretty 10-7 suited

01:13:22.480 --> 01:13:24.550
and not even get to
see a flop with it.

01:13:24.550 --> 01:13:26.950
But 10-7 offsuit is
a bad enough hand

01:13:26.950 --> 01:13:29.290
where I'm not that sad
if he just goes all in,

01:13:29.290 --> 01:13:30.370
and I have to fold.

01:13:30.370 --> 01:13:33.130
So that's why I'm
raising my good hands

01:13:33.130 --> 01:13:37.050
and also my weakest
possible hands

01:13:37.050 --> 01:13:40.930
that I'm OK if I don't
get to see a flop with.

01:13:40.930 --> 01:13:43.660
He does call unfortunately,
but we do hit a great flop.

01:13:43.660 --> 01:13:46.360
So I'm just going to
bet and get it all in.

01:13:46.360 --> 01:13:49.540
Heads up basically any
top pair is, in general,

01:13:49.540 --> 01:13:53.540
just way more good enough to
put all your money in with.

01:13:53.540 --> 01:13:54.610
He folds, though.

01:13:54.610 --> 01:13:55.740
So ace-6, we raise.

01:13:55.740 --> 01:13:57.490
I'm going to go fairly
quickly because I'm

01:13:57.490 --> 01:13:58.885
running a bit short of time.

01:13:58.885 --> 01:14:03.760
We continuation bet the
flop and take it down.

01:14:03.760 --> 01:14:04.420
He raises here.

01:14:04.420 --> 01:14:08.650
I call with king-6, which
is pretty borderline.

01:14:08.650 --> 01:14:11.590
It's too good a hand to
fold, but probably it's

01:14:11.590 --> 01:14:12.700
too bad a hand to call.

01:14:12.700 --> 01:14:14.740
Probably I should
have just raised

01:14:14.740 --> 01:14:16.550
by the same logic as before.

01:14:16.550 --> 01:14:17.530
But we call.

01:14:17.530 --> 01:14:19.510
And I decide to donk
out on this flop

01:14:19.510 --> 01:14:24.690
because I figured there's a
number of draws I can have.

01:14:24.690 --> 01:14:26.710
And here I do have a weak draw.

01:14:26.710 --> 01:14:30.800
A 7 gives me a bad
streak but still

01:14:30.800 --> 01:14:32.920
a very good hand in
the two-player pot.

01:14:32.920 --> 01:14:33.480
He calls.

01:14:33.480 --> 01:14:35.560
And the turn is a
jack, which I still

01:14:35.560 --> 01:14:38.260
have a straight draw because
now a queen gives me a straight.

01:14:38.260 --> 01:14:41.020
So I continue bluffing.

01:14:41.020 --> 01:14:44.010
So he folds, which is good.

01:14:44.010 --> 01:14:47.240
6-2 offsuit I just
give one to them.

01:14:47.240 --> 01:14:49.300
So yeah, I think you
should be playing

01:14:49.300 --> 01:14:51.280
90-95% percent of buttons.

01:14:51.280 --> 01:14:53.680
Maybe not that high when
it's getting shallower,

01:14:53.680 --> 01:14:55.590
but at least 80% of buttons.

01:14:55.590 --> 01:14:59.470
But 2-3 offsuit is one of the
hands I'm OK with folding.

01:14:59.470 --> 01:15:02.320
8-5 suited, I'm just
check-raising this flopping,

01:15:02.320 --> 01:15:03.970
getting it in.

01:15:03.970 --> 01:15:04.730
He folds-- yeah?

01:15:04.730 --> 01:15:06.610
AUDIENCE: Let's say
you had an opponent

01:15:06.610 --> 01:15:10.650
that from the big blind was
very likely to three-bet you.

01:15:10.650 --> 01:15:12.850
How would you adjust
your range opening

01:15:12.850 --> 01:15:14.440
from the button or
the small blind?

01:15:14.440 --> 01:15:17.660
WILL MA: Oh, OK.

01:15:17.660 --> 01:15:19.690
So if they're really
loose, you would basically

01:15:19.690 --> 01:15:22.210
raise only your good
hands that you're hoping

01:15:22.210 --> 01:15:23.481
they reraise all in with.

01:15:23.481 --> 01:15:23.980
And--

01:15:23.980 --> 01:15:27.020
AUDIENCE: So would that be
from maybe 60% of your hands

01:15:27.020 --> 01:15:27.870
down from 80?

01:15:27.870 --> 01:15:29.910
WILL MA: Oh, yeah.

01:15:29.910 --> 01:15:31.330
You would basically raise less.

01:15:31.330 --> 01:15:33.074
So it'd just have more
value essentially.

01:15:33.074 --> 01:15:35.240
AUDIENCE: It's hard to
calibrate that range, though,

01:15:35.240 --> 01:15:36.640
as what's a good hand.

01:15:36.640 --> 01:15:39.280
WILL MA: Yeah, and also another
thing you can do is call more.

01:15:39.280 --> 01:15:41.620
I don't think it gets relevant
in this heads up match.

01:15:41.620 --> 01:15:43.382
But sometimes it
gets shallow enough

01:15:43.382 --> 01:15:45.340
where you actually want
to have a calling range

01:15:45.340 --> 01:15:48.740
preflop from the button.

01:15:48.740 --> 01:15:52.210
OK, so king-10.

01:15:52.210 --> 01:15:53.810
OK, so I do call here.

01:15:53.810 --> 01:15:55.960
I think I essentially
call, thinking

01:15:55.960 --> 01:15:58.340
I would call if he went
all in but also just

01:15:58.340 --> 01:16:01.930
to make it so that I
can also sometimes call

01:16:01.930 --> 01:16:04.070
a hand like 10-4 offsuit.

01:16:04.070 --> 01:16:07.190
And he can't just shove any
2 and expect me to fold.

01:16:07.190 --> 01:16:08.840
So I decide to call here.

01:16:08.840 --> 01:16:13.910
We get a great flop, so I
check it back as a slow play.

01:16:13.910 --> 01:16:15.470
He checks again on the turn.

01:16:15.470 --> 01:16:16.970
So I bet.

01:16:16.970 --> 01:16:18.470
He calls.

01:16:18.470 --> 01:16:20.750
The river he leads
out quite big.

01:16:20.750 --> 01:16:24.890
And I just call because I
think raising I'll usually only

01:16:24.890 --> 01:16:26.840
get called by better.

01:16:26.840 --> 01:16:28.850
And he actually turns
up a flush here.

01:16:28.850 --> 01:16:30.530
So it's a weird hand.

01:16:30.530 --> 01:16:32.450
It seems like we could
have lost a lot more.

01:16:32.450 --> 01:16:34.850
But I'm not saying our
opponent played the hand badly,

01:16:34.850 --> 01:16:38.280
but we were very lucky to
lose this little when we have

01:16:38.280 --> 01:16:40.640
a two pair against a flush.

01:16:40.640 --> 01:16:45.290
And we only lost, essentially,
four big blinds or something.

01:16:45.290 --> 01:16:48.100
I guess I'll be happy
to get away with that.

